OpenStreetMap Data Case Study¶

Map Area¶

San Jose, CA, United States

  • (https://mapzen.com/data/metro-extracts/metro/san-jose_california/)

This map is close to my home town and I am interested in knowing all the interesting facts that I can find with my queries.

Problems Encountered in the Map¶

After initially downloading and uncompressing the file, I made a small sample file of size 29 MB. I used the data.py python code to run this sample file. I noticed the following problems with the data.

  • Abbreviated street names ("N. Mathilda Ave","Wolfe Rd.")
  • Inconsistent city names ("SUnnyvale","San Jos","San Jose")
  • Inconsistent postal codes ("CA 95054","95014-2225", "95014")
  • Inconsistent phone numbers("1 408 732 4222","1.408.245.5620","+1-800-POLYCOM")

Abbreviated Street Names¶

I was able to find most of the inconsistencies in the street names of the sample.osm file using print statements in data.py. To clean the abbreviated street names I used dictionaries for look-ups. Here is the snippet of the code used to clean the street names and the resulting fixed names.

In [ ]:
def update_addr_name(name, mapping):
    newname = ''
    #replace N with North,S with South etc.
    if name.split()[0] in direction_addr:
        for key,val in direction.iteritems():
            name = name.replace(key,val)
    if name in expand_addr:
        newname = expand_addr[name]
        print name,' ----> ',newname
        return (newname)
    #replace 1st with 'First' etc.
    name_list = name.split()
    for items in name_list:
        if items in street_num:
            for key,val in street_num.iteritems():
                name = name.replace(key,val)
        
    last_word = name.split()[-1]
    if last_word in mapping_addr:
        #get the words except the last one
        for n in range(len(name.split())-1):
            newname += name.split()[n]
            newname +=' '
        newname += mapping_addr[last_word]
        print name,' ----> ',newname
        return newname
    else:
        return name

Inconsistent City Names¶

To clean the city names I used dictionary 'mapping_city' for look-ups to match city names with accent on letters, lower case etc. Here is the snippet of the code with a part of its output.

In [ ]:
def update_city_name(name,mapping):
    new_name=''
    if name in mapping_city: 
        new_name = mapping_city[name]
        print name,' ----> ',repr(new_name)
        return repr(new_name)
    else:
        return repr(name)

Inconsistent Postcodes¶

Some of the postcodes had 9-digits, some had 5-digits and some had the state name in them. To clean up I used regex (POSTCODE = re.compile(r'[9][0-9]{4}$') to match the 5-digit postcode and changed the remaining postcodes to 5-digits to be consistent. The state name was stripped from the postcode and only the postcode was retained. Here is a snippet of the code and a part of its output.

In [ ]:
def update_postcode(postcode):
    if POSTCODE.match(postcode):
        return postcode
    elif postcode.split()[0] == 'CA':
        print postcode,' ---->',postcode.split()[1]
        return (postcode.split()[1])
    else:
        print postcode,' ----> ',postcode.split('-')[0]
        return (postcode.split('-')[0])

Inconsistent Phone Numbers¶

The phone numbers were in many different formats and they were made into a standard format: (xxx) xxx-xxxx I used a regex function PHONENUM =re.compile(r'[4,5,6,8][0-9]{2}-[0-9]{3}-[0-9]{4}$') to get all the phone numbers which were in standard form. The rest of the phone numbers were parsed with extra +1,'.' etc removed and made into standard form. Here is a snippet of the code and its output. There were two wrong phone numbers - one with just '+1' and the second with just 7 digits. Both were tagged 'Invalid phone number'.

In [ ]:
def update_phone(phonenum):
    if PHONENUM.match(phonenum):
        return phonenum
    else:
        new_num=''
        count = 0
        for i in range(len(phonenum)):
        #get the first number
            if (phonenum[i] in ['4','5','6','8']) and count == 0:
                new_num += "("
                new_num += phonenum[i]
                count +=1
            elif (count > 0) and (count <= 12):
                if phonenum[i].isalnum():
                    new_num += phonenum[i]
                    count +=1
                    if count == 3:
                        new_num+= ") "
                    if count == 6:
                        if new_num[6].isdigit():
                            new_num += "-"
    if len(new_num) > 9 and len(new_num) <=14:
        print phonenum,' ----> ',new_num
        return new_num    
    else:
        print 'Invalid phone number: ',phonenum
        return ('Invalid phone number')

Addtional Suggestions¶

It would be great to include local farmer's markets and ice skating information.

To improve the quality of the data, I suggest that there should a standard format that the users can enter the data or the system should reject. We can use machine learning to learn the existing data and check on new data being entered and flag for errors.

Conclusion¶

The OpenStreetMap of San Jose, California is of reasonably good quality that has an immense depth of information but has some minor typos and different formats of the same data (example: phone numbers entered are of very different formats, city name with and without accent etc.). This is inevitable since there are so many contributing users. An easy fix may be to use a script to check the format or flag error message when incorrect format is entered by the user.
